In December 2012 in the Central African Republic, conflict continues to worsen living conditions in what is already one of the world’s poorest countries, with one of the highest rates of under-five child mortality. Vital infrastructure has been destroyed, severely constricting access to healthcare, education and other basic services. Additionally, numerous national and foreign armed groups continue to forcibly recruit children, using them as guards, combatants, domestic servants and sex slaves, among other roles. UNICEF supports transit centres that help children overcome some of the effects of the abuse, exploitation and violence to which they have been subjected and in which they have participated. The centres provide shelter, psychosocial support, health care, education and vocational opportunities while working to reintegrate children with their families. Worldwide, thousands of children remain deprived of their most basic rights through association with armed forces and groups. UNICEF continues to advocate for their release and supports ongoing rehabilitation efforts that, since 1998, have assisted more than 100,000 children to reintegrate with their communities.";s:17:"created_timestamp";i:1354579200;s:9:"copyright";s:871:"© Notice: UNICEF photographs are copyrighted and may not be reproduced in any medium without written permission from authorized UNICEF staff. Permission is available to UNICEF partners and bonafide national/international media for specified use relating to UNICEF-supported issues or programmes. Permissions are granted for one-time use in a context that accurately represents the real situation and identity of all human beings depicted. All reproductions MUST be credited, including, at a minimum, the copyright symbol - © - UNICEF and the last name of the photographer. Reproductions without credit are not authorized. Image content may not be changed by digital or any other means, except cropping. Images may not be used in a commercial context; 