UNICEF partner TPO operates two Child Friendly Spaces (CFS) in Mwenga Center, South Kivu, DRC, providing nearly 4,000 children aged 2-18 with a protected environment in which to gather, supervised by staff trained in child protection. Designed to support and encourage their freedom of expression, right to play, to learn, to be stimulated and to develop their capacities in a friendly and warm environment, Child Friendly Spaces also offer an opportunity to sensitize children on basic issues like hygiene and sanitation, as well as the importance of education.


“UNICEF funds our project in Mwenga, which is designed to reinforce the capacity of the community to respond on behalf of their vulnerable children,” explains Rwaha Rwakenga, a Social Worker for TPO, a Uganda-based NGO. “One day we’re not going to be here, but the community must carry on with serving and protecting their children. For this reason the community is involved not only in the CFS, but also in trainings and sensitizations to make sure everyone in the community is aware of the importance of this for their children.”";s:17:"created_timestamp";i:1368724988;s:9:"copyright";s:24:"©UNICEF DRC/2013/Morton";s:12:"focal_length";i:0;s:3:"iso";i:0;s:13:"shutter_speed";i:0;s:5:"title";s:0:"";}}

a:5:{s:5:"width";i:640;s:6:"height";i:428;s:4:"file";s:32:"2014/04/130528100749-640x428.jpg";s:5:"sizes";a:2:{s:9:"thumbnail";a:4:{s:4:"file";s:32:"130528100749-640x428-150x150.jpg";s:5:"width";i:150;s:6:"height";i:150;s:9:"mime-type";s:10:"image/jpeg";}s:6:"medium";a:4:{s:4:"file";s:32:"130528100749-640x428-300x200.jpg";s:5:"width";i:300;s:6:"height";i:200;s:9:"mime-type";s:10:"image/jpeg";}}s:10:"image_meta";a:10:{s:8:"aperture";i:0;s:6:"credit";s:12:"Brett Morton";s:6:"camera";s:0:"";s:7:"caption";s:1545:"Buhimba Temporary Site. Following months of relative peace after the takeover of Goma by the M23 rebels in November, 2012, fighting once again broke out on the edge of Goma between the M23 and the Congolese Army (FARDC) in May, 2013. Upwards of 6,000 people fled their homes towards the city center, where they sought shelter in schools, churches, or with host families.
In response to the displacement the humanitarian community mobilized resources to create numerous temporary sites to cater to the displaced. UNICEF coordinated with partners Norwegian Refugee Council (NRC) and Norwegian Church Aid (NCA) to provide shelter and Water, Sanitation and Hygiene as well as logistical support to the management of the sites.
With more than 1,700 families staying at the Sotraki site (as of 04 June, 2013) UNICEF partner NCA responded within one week of the displacement to construct 16 latrines,12 showers, and instal a 30m3 water bladder which provides a constant flow to 12 taps in the site. In addition, NCA hygiene teams have organized and supervised the regular cleaning of the latrines, as well as spreading general hygiene messages. NRC has contributed to the establishment of numerous tents in which to hose the displaced in both the Sotraki and Buhimba sites. In addition, through UNICEF RRMP funds, NRC has provided transportation of displaced to the Buhimba site in an effort to decongest the Sotraki site. Plans are underway for an NFI distribution to be carried out through UNICEF RRMP partners NRC and Slidarités International.";s:17:"created_timestamp";i:1369735669;s:9:"copyright";s:24:"©UNICEF DRC/2013/Morton";s:12:"focal_length";i:0;s:3:"iso";i:0;s:13:"shutter_speed";i:0;s:5:"title";s:0:"";}}
